{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653684"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:47:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:47:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18589"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18589"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79557"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11321"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64861"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10386"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27201"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79557"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe prefrontal cortex is the anterior portion of the frontal lobes and is highly developed in humans compared to other species.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its primary function?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Processing of basic sensory information","Generation of motor commands","Integration of complex cognitive behaviors","Production of speech sounds","Storage of long-term memories"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eintegration of complex cognitive behaviors\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the prefrontal cortex. This region coordinates higher-order functions including executive control, decision-making, personality, and social behavior through its extensive connections with other brain regions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcessing of basic sensory information\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily performed by specific sensory cortices (visual, auditory, somatosensory)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneration of motor commands\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily a function of the primary motor cortex and premotor areas\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of speech sounds\u003C/strong\u003E - While the frontal lobe contains Broca\u0027s area for speech production, this is distinct from the prefrontal cortex\u0027s cognitive functions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStorage of long-term memories\u003C/strong\u003E - This primarily involves the temporal lobe and hippocampus\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe prefrontal cortex receives input from multiple brain regions and uses this information to guide appropriate behavioral responses and complex decision-making.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The prefrontal cortex integrates sensory information and regulates complex cognitive behaviors.","The prefrontal cortex maintains extensive connections with other brain regions to coordinate higher-order functions.","The prefrontal cortex is essential for personality, decision-making, and social behavior."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":